Identify Common Issues with Axe Accessibility Linter

02
On this page
  1. Install axe-linter for Visual Studio Code
  2. Writing Useful Image Descriptions with the alt Decision Tree
    1. 📝 Exercise: Find the Missing Alt Text

Install axe-linter for Visual Studio Code

If you are a VSCode user, I suggest installing the axe Accessibility Linter extension from the Visual Studio Code Marketplace. Similar to tools like ESLint, axe-linter will highlight common accessibility issues in your project files and suggest fixes.

After installing the plugin, open up header.html from inside the _includes directory.

If axe-linter identifies issues, it will underline the offending line with a red squiggly line and color the file names red in the sidebar. Hovering over a squiggly line with an issue will display a popup with information. Issues are also gathered in a Problems tab in VS Code’s built-in Terminal.

Inside of the code for our navigation mega menu, axe-linter found that we were using image tags without including alternate text.

Writing Useful Image Descriptions with the alt Decision Tree

While adding an alt attribute will fix the issues found by axe-linter, it's good to learn how to write thoughtful image descriptions.

We'll start by investigating the images included in our nav menu.

There is a photo of a person reading a map associated with the "All sites" link, and an image of an RV associated with the "RV parks" option.

But what should we write in the alt text?

The W3C put together a super helpful alt Decision Tree resource to provide guidance.

Following the tree, we are prompted with several questions like:

  • Does the image contain text?
  • Is it used for a link or button?
  • Does it contribute meaning to the page, or is it purely decorative?

For these nav menu images, it could be argued either way if they contribute to the content of the menu. If you think a person using a screen reader would benefit from a description of the images in the MegaNav, add some alt text. Otherwise, set the alt to a blank string and the screen reader won’t announce it.

Axe-linter found another missing alt attribute for the tents.jpg image on the homepage.

In this case the tents.jpg image does add content to the page. We could set the alt text to "A festival of tents at sunset".

Once all of the issues found by axe-linter have been addressed, the file in the sidebar will no longer be highlighted in red and it will go away from the Problems tab.

📝 Exercise: Find the Missing Alt Text

As you continue through the workshop, fill in missing image alt text issues as you come across them.
